	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>SnibbsQ said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">The issue isn't blaming the violence on the guns, but being weary of the extent to which guns enable violent acts. Also, just by the numbers, you're more likely to get shot by your own gun than anyone else's. Unfortunately, history has set us up to be unable to really manage a gun ban in a fashion similar to many European countries. At this point, guns are so ubiquitous on our continent that if we were to implement a ban, you'd be damned sure that drugs would no longer be the big money makers being smuggled in.<br />
<br />
This is almost a blessing in the long-run, however, as it, in theory, forces us to address these issues at their root rather than the symptoms. Make no mistake, though, accessible guns aren't not enabling violence and it is certainly absurd to assert otherwise. But, like I said, it's a moot point pretty much. I grew up in a hunting state, I've been hunting, I see use for guns other than puerile entertainment. If I had children, though, I certainly would not let them go to a home wherein guns were stored--as I said, at the end of the day, the guns you own are more a danger to yourself and those you care about than to anyone else and EVERY gun owner thinks they are acting responsibly until their 12 year old shoots his playdate by accident because that one time they just happened to forget to lock the gun cabinet.<br />
<br />
Tivia, I believe the knife attack in China didn't leave anyone dead, did it?</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>The reason the numbers show you are more likely to get shot with your own gun is because people should require training to handle one but they aren't. The fact is most fun owners are like most drivers, woefully untrained with little to no concept of the level of responsibility.<br />
<br />
As for the knife attack, I really don't know. I heard there were, but I don't care enough about either attack to dig into the details. My only point was, people looking to cause violence and death are going to find a method, legal or not.</div>
