</div>DAMN THOSE FUN OWNERS AND THEIR FUN! Ok, back to topic...<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">As for the knife attack, I really don't know. I heard there were, but I don't care enough about either attack to dig into the details. My only point was, people looking to cause violence and death are going to find a method, legal or not.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>I'm not so sure about your claim regarding &quot;most&quot; gun owners, to be honest. But, at the end of the day, it is what it is and, more importantly, those gun owners think they are being responsible.<br />
<br />
My point about the knife attacks, though, assuming the number of deaths was small (I swear, I recall reading that there was only one death), is that there is a significant difference between violence that does not result in actual death and violence that does. If our society saw no difference, the sentencing for murder and battery would be the same.<br />
<br />
After all is said and done, we actually seem to agree that gun bans are probably not the answer but stricter regulation (increased training requirements) is a worthwhile pursuit. However, this line that &quot;if someone wants to cause harm, they're going to cause harm&quot; is shoddy reasoning--by that reasoning any and all dangerous items should be allowed to the general public, be they bombs, gasses, poisons, what have you. The debate is whether or not the societal damage and unease caused by access to such an item is outweighed by the satisfaction of having it (because, let's be honest here, beyond hunting there is little practical purpose to a firearm in the hands of &quot;just some guy&quot;).</div>
