</div>I don't think anyone is trying to deny the perpetrator's culpability. But you seem to imply that it is worthless to discuss underlying causes--perhaps you are simply ignoring them by accident or perhaps you believe in some Leibnizian monadic metaphysics where human beings ultimately exist in vacuum and are not susceptible to outside influences. I, and others like me, on the other hand, believe that people are mechanisms, to one degree or another, and their actions are influenced and perhaps even driven by outside influences. So, yes, the guy is culpable, but we should also look at what potentially influenced him and whether or not they can be addressed so, you know, this **** doesn't occur again or as frequently.<br />
