    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_533251">Again, there are problems with that sort of solution.<br />
<br />
Banning the manufacturing of firearms will result in mass unemployment of people who have ready access to said firearms.<br />
<br />
Who will fund the buyback programs?  The public, of course, via increased taxes.  Increasing taxes on ammo will not make a significant dent in the funding required for this.<br />
<br />
And perhaps the most important thing is that this will only keep the honest people honest.  Those who would use guns to commit crimes will hoard ammo and weapons and, once again, create a large black market for these.<br />
<br />
A slow decline of firearms in the US over decades is wildly optimistic.  More realistically there will be a large immediate hit, accompanied with protests and violent riots (remember that this is a constitutional right that you're changing), followed by a smaller gradual decline, to which we would reach a still-significant baseline controlled by smuggling rings / crime syndicates.  Remember that prohibition thing?  It will follow much the same pattern as that.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
<br>
