    <div align="left" id="post_message_533260"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>SnibbsQ said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">I don't think anyone is trying to deny the perpetrator's culpability. But you seem to imply that it is worthless to discuss underlying causes--perhaps you are simply ignoring them by accident or perhaps you believe in some Leibnizian monadic metaphysics where human beings ultimately exist in vacuum and are not susceptible to outside influences. I, and others like me, on the other hand, believe that people are mechanisms, to one degree or another, and their actions are influenced and perhaps even driven by outside influences. So, yes, the guy is culpable, but we should also look at what potentially influenced him and whether or not they can be addressed so, you know, this **** doesn't occur again or as frequently.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>The 'influencing' stuff has gotten way out of hand. It's not video games like the media likes to believe (if it were we'd have a WHOLE lot more of these type of shootings, like one every other day), it's not Mass Effect like the facebook commentators on his brother's page like to believe (if it were man, it would be easy to stop these things) - I mean leaving aside that they had the wrong guy and were still eager to blame it all on Mass Effect because of his brother's facebook page... It sure isn't owning guns, if that were all it took there would just be constant shootouts.<br />
<br />
People keep trying to find 'that thing that is the single cause of this' because it's an easy fix... if we can just find out WHICH media item made him do it we can ban that particular item and it will never happen again. That's the mindset that always seems to arise during these type of tragedies for quite a lot of people... only it doesn't work that way because it has to be a very complex combination of environment, nurture and nature or we'd have isolated this already. None of us here on the internet have all the information needed to put together all those factors about this guy, or the last guy. I mean we know there's a tendency for them to be socially isolated but if that were all it took every weird loner guy on your street would have shot someone by now. Quite frankly it's starting to bug the crap out of me. Complex problems like this usually don't have a single identifiable thing that you can go 'oh, yeah it was that one song that made him kill people'. Except I guess in the case of that one guy who had a history of harming children his own age, and neighborhood pets, and then going off his anti-psychotic medication for a long time and isolating himself but yeah it was totally just video games that made him kill people.<br />
<br />
It's the same type of ******** you see on every damn TV station, playing the 'blame that thing' game, and it's not helping. Hell, I'd like to see less about 'what made so and so do it' and more 'lets not even mention that guy's name so they gain zero fame and instead focus on the victims' approach to these tragedies. That's the one thing I absolutely love my city's police force for, when they found the guy who put a bomb outside our parliament building they withheld his name and were insistent that his manifesto not be published - which it wasn't. They denied him the fame he wanted and I love them for that.</div>
