    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_533327">I used to be a gun collector and I love target practice.<br />
However, ever since becoming a father and reading more and more about the country comparisons (killing sprees, gun ownership, gun deaths, etc, per capita) , I am more and more willing to support stricter gun control regulations.<br />
I also know of 3 people that have easily killed themselves with their or their parent's guns as well, so this isn't just about homicide.  A gun in the home means you literally only have to contract a finger to end a life, and if you're impulsive or you have kids, it can be a terrible thing to have around.<br />
<br />
People that mention black market if guns became outlawed?  I don't know of any black market dealers... I couldn't find drugs if I wanted to, how could I find someone willing to risk massive jail time to sell illegal guns?  Whether there's a black market or not, the fact that it's an underground market still makes it a barrier for many if not most people.  But at least here in the south, it probably wouldn't make a big difference, or it would take decades or centuries before ban became effective.<br />
<br />
A background check simply checks for a criminal history.  That does nothing -  most of these killers don't have any criminal history.  I don't know if there could be some sort of mental battery exam that could help weed out some of these things.  There are probably enough Psychologists to handle that workload, though (it's a career a lot of people go into but there are limited positions outside of private practice).  And that also does nothing if the guns end up stolen.<br />
<br />
In some Scandinavian countries, gun safes are required as well.  That's a decent idea, but that does nothing if child/relative knows safe's combo or has access to the key.<br />
<br />
Here in Texas, I can literally buy and own a gun within minutes.  They call in a background check and it takes just a few minutes for it to run before I'm approved and walking out with a gun and ammo.  At Gun shows it's even easier, and you can legally buy even more &quot;dangerous&quot; guns there that aren't sold in shops (used guns that fall outside of a ban's regulations based on when they were manufactured).<br />
<br />
The idea that an armed citizen could have saved the day is also a big assumption to make, especially in cases where nobody or everybody exercises that right.  First of all, what if no teacher WANTS to own a gun or have that responsibility?  What if they're a poor shot and end up killing a kid in the process instead?  And how about that loaded guns around curious children carries a risk of its own, regardless of any killers being around?  And lastly, how could that hypothetical scenario always play out in a good way?  Isn't it just as likely someone thinks the armed vigilante citizen is the killer, and vigilante gets unjustly killed?  Or that killer kills vigilante and now has another weapon + ammo to inflict additional damage with?<br />
<br />
I don't know what the solution is.  Guns are so entrenched in our culture.  <br />
<br />
Here in Texas pretty much every household owns a gun for &quot;home defense&quot; and it's so patently stupid.  If someone breaks into your house, they want to steal something and sell it, they don't want to kill you, and they probably break in when nobody's home anyway (although this is argument FOR gun ownership as well).  But then a ton of those &quot;home defense&quot; guns end up being the cause of suicide or accidental gun deaths because the owner doesn't have them locked up properly in case they &quot;need to get to it quickly&quot;.  My best suggested compromise there is to keep a pump shotgun but no ammo for it, and if someone intrudes, simply pump it once.  Anyone hearing that is going to run... But honestly?  If you live in the sticks, nobody is going to break into your house in the first place.<br />
<br />
It's crazy how paranoid many Americans are.  Or maybe it's just a paranoid fantasy.  <br />
<br />
I think media circus not ever naming the killer and airing his photo and background all the time would be a start.  Talk about him but don't show his photo or say his name.  I think drum magazines are unnecessary and I don't see the harm in them being banned, regardless of if/when they've been used in attacks (even though they make target shooting easier).  Besides that?  I don't know what we can do.  <br />
<br />
Better mental health care only helps if shooter actually tries to seek help or wants to help themselves after being committed by someone else.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
