</div>I don't think that using personal experience really applies here.  You would be surprised at how easy it is to obtain illegal drugs.  I've never had any desire to myself, but I've known people that were able to get pot and ecstasy whom I never would have thought had the connections to.<br />
<br />
I guess you're right about the fact that it would be difficult to find somebody willing to risk massive jail time for massive profit, though.  If anything, history has shown us that prison is an effective deterrent for dealing with smuggling, black market dealing, murder, or anything else that could illegally turn a profit.<br />
<br />
I'm sorry for the sarcasm.  If it seemed too bitter it wasn't meant to be, it was simply an effective way to make my point.  On a more serious note, though, you're certainly right about it taking decades or centuries for the ban to be effective at all.  Though with the aforementioned black market potential, I don't think that it will ever be effective enough until guns are replaced by some other point-and-kill technology.</div>
