    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_533376"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Pearll said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">I don't think that using personal experience really applies here.  You would be surprised at how easy it is to obtain illegal drugs.  I've never had any desire to myself, but I've known people that were able to get pot and ecstasy whom I never would have thought had the connections to.<br />
<br />
I guess you're right about the fact that it would be difficult to find somebody willing to risk massive jail time for massive profit, though.  If anything, history has shown us that prison is an effective deterrent for dealing with smuggling, black market dealing, murder, or anything else that could illegally turn a profit.<br />
<br />
I'm sorry for the sarcasm.  If it seemed too bitter it wasn't meant to be, it was simply an effective way to make my point.  On a more serious note, though, you're certainly right about it taking decades or centuries for the ban to be effective at all.  Though with the aforementioned black market potential, I don't think that it will ever be effective enough until guns are replaced by some other point-and-kill technology.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>You seemed to miss the most important sentence: &quot;Whether there's a black market or not, the fact that it's an underground market still makes it <b>a barrier for many if not most people</b>&quot;.  I can walk into a store and buy a ton of guns right now without having to try to find a shady dealer, even in a rural area with no large population center nearby.  I can even buy guns online and have them shipped to nearest gun range for pick up, of which there are 4 within 30 minutes of me (and I live in the country).  There's also pawn shops and gun shops I could get them from or have them delivered to.  If I had a FFL  (not difficult to get, just have to wait a while for turnaround), I could even buy them online and have them delivered directly to me.<br />
<br />
And yes, pot and ecstasy probably are easy to find, especially in cities or if you're college age.  But harder drugs and illegal guns?  You cannot tell me there wouldn't be a bit of a barrier there buying guns illegally compared to just walking into a number of stores or ordering them online.<br />
<br />
Now, whether that barrier is enough to make a difference?  And whether or not it would even be relevant (a motivated killer would steal guns or make bombs, etc)?  That's another issue altogether, hence my remark about it taking decades if not centuries for a gun ban to work here (at least in the South).  But like I alluded to, there's a big issue with gun deaths in general even outside of killing sprees, so my post was just a general ramble of concern about our large number of gun deaths with no clear solution.  I'm just saying I wouldn't mind stricter gun control at this point even if it doesn't make a big difference here in Texas.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
